         KB Home CFO Raymond Silcock leaves builder
    








    By
        
        Dawn Wotapka

Published: Dec 18, 2009 9:14 a.m. ET

Share


















































 



 




















By

                                        DawnWotapka







NEW YORK (MarketWatch) -- Home-building company KB Home 

                            
                            
                                  
      
      
      
      
      
      
      
                                  
                                    KBH, -0.26%

                            
                                  
      
      
      
      
      
      
      
                                         which is being investigated by the Securities and Exchange Commission, said Thursday that Chief Financial Officer Raymond P. Silcock left the company on December 14. William R. Hollinger, who has served as senior vice president and chief accounting officer since 2007, will be the company's principal financial officer, pending the selection of a new CFO. Silcock will receive a lump-sum payment of $200,000 and six months of salary, or an aggregate of $300,000, according to a filing with the SEC. The company provided no reason for Silcock's leaving. NEW YORK (MarketWatch) -- Home-builder KB Home KBH, which is being investigated by the Securities and Exchange Commission, disclosed late Thursday that Chief Financial Officer Raymond P. Silcock left the company Monday. The Los Angeles-based company, the nation's fifth-largest builder by annual closings, provided no reason for Silcock's departure, which was mutual. Representatives weren't immediately available for comment. William R. Hollinger, who has served as senior vice president and chief accounting officer since 2007, becomes principal financial officer, pending the selection of a new CFO. Silcock will receive a lump-sum payment of $200,000--the bonus he was guaranteed in connection with his hire--and six months of salary, or an aggregate of $300,000, according to a filing with the SEC. This news follows the October disclosure that the SEC issued a "formal order of investigation . . . regarding possible accounting and disclosure issues." The exact reason remains unclear: A spokeswoman had no further detail earlier Thursday. In recent years, KB Home also has been rocked by scandals over manipulation of stock options paid to its chief executive and by federal charges that it engaged in improper mortgage lending. In November 2006, Bruce Karatz resigned as chief executive of KB after an internal investigation found he backdated his own stock option grants to increase his pay. In September 2008, Karatz agreed to pay more than $7 million to settle securities charges with the SEC but didn't admit any wrongdoing in the backdating case. His lawyer, John Keker, said then that Karatz acted "appropriately." In mid-2005, KB agreed to pay $3.2 million to settle federal allegations that its mortgage unit engaged in poor practices. The U.S. Department of Housing and Urban Development charged that a KB subsidiary made it possible for ineligible borrowers to get mortgages guaranteed by the Federal Housing Administration. Like other home builders, KB has suffered heavy losses in recent years amid plunging demand and the need to write down the value of land. KB reported a net loss of $66 million for the fiscal third quarter ended Aug. 31, compared with a year-earlier loss of $144.7 million. It is scheduled to report results for its fourth quarter Jan. 12. Shares of KB Home were up slightly after hours at $13.32. NEW YORK (MarketWatch) -- Home-builder KB Home KBH, which is being investigated by the Securities and Exchange Commission, disclosed late Thursday that Chief Financial Officer Raymond P. Silcock left the company Monday after about three months. The Los Angeles-based company, the nation's fifth-largest builder by annual closings, provided no reason for Silcock's departure, saying in a statement that the two parties "mutually agreed to conclude his employment." Representatives weren't immediately available for further comment. William R. Hollinger, who has served as senior vice president and chief accounting officer since 2007, becomes principal financial officer, pending the selection of a new CFO. Silcock was a recent arrival at KB Home, having joined in September. Previously, he served as CFO of UST Inc., a consumer products concern. From KB Home, Silcock will receive a lump-sum payment of $200,000--the bonus he was guaranteed in connection with his hire--and six months of salary, or an aggregate of $300,000, according to a filing with the SEC. This news follows the October disclosure that the SEC issued a "formal order of investigation ... regarding possible accounting and disclosure issues." The exact reason remains unclear: A spokeswoman had no further detail earlier Thursday. In recent years, KB Home also has been rocked by scandals over manipulation of stock options paid to its chief executive and by federal charges that it engaged in improper mortgage lending. In November 2006, Bruce Karatz resigned as chief executive of KB after an internal investigation found he backdated his own stock option grants to increase his pay. In September 2008, Karatz agreed to pay more than $7 million to settle securities charges with the SEC but didn't admit any wrongdoing in the backdating case. His lawyer, John Keker, said then that Karatz acted "appropriately." In mid-2005, KB agreed to pay $3.2 million to settle federal allegations that its mortgage unit engaged in poor practices. The U.S. Department of Housing and Urban Development charged that a KB subsidiary made it possible for ineligible borrowers to get mortgages guaranteed by the Federal Housing Administration. Like other home builders, KB has suffered heavy losses in recent years amid plunging demand and the need to write down the value of land. KB reported a net loss of $66 million for the fiscal third quarter ended Aug. 31, compared with a year-earlier loss of $144.7 million. It is scheduled to report results for its fourth quarter Jan. 12. Shares of KB Home were up slightly after hours at $13.32.


